and the eldest sons of barons and the uncles of lords were called <i>Masters</i>, but this is not primarily a Scottish surname.","German: dialect form of   Meister   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"McMaster","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac an Mháighistir</i> ‘son of the master’, meaning ‘teacher’ or ‘cleric’. It could also be applied in the sense of ‘lord’ or ‘owner’. This name was sometimes Anglicized as   Masterson  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Masterson Esq was born about 1401, in Nantwich, Cheshire, England, his father, Richard Masterson, was 28 and his mother, Joan De Egerton, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Cicely Leycester of Tabley. He died in 1435, in his hometown, at the age of 35."},"et":{"about 1401–1435":"umbes 1401–1435","1401–1435":"1401–1435","1401–Female":"1401–Surnud","1400–1483":"1400–1483","1431–1468":"1431–1468","1374–1447":"1374–1447","1376–Female":"1376–Surnud","1447":"1447","1435":"1435","1468":"1468","1401":"1401","1400":"1400","1376":"1376","1431":"1431","1396":"1396","1374":"1374","about 1401":"umbes 1401","1483":"1483","about 1431":"umbes 1431","Nantwich, Cheshire, England":"Nantwich, Cheshire, England","Hatton, Cheshire, , England":"Hatton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1401–1435":"noin 1401–1435","1401–1435":"1401–1435","1401–Female":"1401–Kuollut","1400–1483":"1400–1483","1431–1468":"1431–1468","1374–1447":